## Theorem: translated_imo_2010_p2

Theorem: translated_imo_2010_p2
Given: a b c = triangle a b c
Given: o = circle o a b c
Given: i = incenter i a b c
Given: d = on_line d a i, on_circle d o a
Given: f = on_line f b c
Given: e = on_aline e a c b a f, on_circle e o a
Given: g = midpoint g i f
Given: k = on_line k d g, on_line k e i
Prove: prove that segment oa = segment ok

Goal: cong o a o k

## English proof (from stage 1)
{
  "key_observation": "Use a coordinate system centered at the circumcenter O, place the triangle symmetrically on the circumcircle, and show that the two lines DG and EI intersect at a point K whose power with respect to the circumcircle equals OA^2, forcing OK = OA.",
  "plan": [
    "Introduce coordinates with O as the origin and the circumcircle as a unit circle.",
    "Express the incenter I and the point D on AI and the circumcircle.",
    "Use the condition defining E to parametrize it on the circumcircle and determine the midpoint G of IF.",
    "Compute the equations of the lines DG and EI and their intersection K.",
    "Show that K lies on the circle centered at O with radius OA, hence OA = OK."
  ],
  "steps": [
    {
      "claim": "We may choose Cartesian coordinates so that O=(0,0) and the circumcircle of triangle ABC is the unit circle.",
      "reasoning": "Since only distances and incidences are relevant, we may apply an affine isometry and a scaling. This sends the circumcenter to the origin and the circumcircle to a circle of radius 1 without changing the statement to be proved up to the same ratio OA = OK.",
      "facts_used": [
        "rigid motions preserve distances",
        "scaling preserves ratios",
        "definition of circumcenter"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "Let A,B,C be points on the unit circle, and let the incenter I have barycentric coordinates proportional to the side lengths a=BC, b=CA, c=AB; equivalently, in vector form I=(aA+bB+cC)/(a+b+c).",
      "reasoning": "This is the standard coordinate description of the incenter of a triangle. It follows from the fact that the incenter is the intersection of the internal angle bisectors.",
      "facts_used": [
        "incenter barycentric formula"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The point D, defined by D lying on line AI and on the circumcircle, is the second intersection of line AI with the unit circle.",
      "reasoning": "Since A lies on the circumcircle and D is on both AI and the circumcircle, D is exactly the other intersection point of that line with the circle.",
      "facts_used": [
        "definition of line intersection with a circle"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The point E is the unique second intersection of the circumcircle with the line through A determined by the angle condition ∠EAC = ∠BAF.",
      "reasoning": "The relation on_aline e a c b a f means the directed angle between EA and AC equals the directed angle between BA and AF. Since E is also on the circumcircle, this fixes E as the unique second point on the circumcircle satisfying that angle condition.",
      "facts_used": [
        "directed angles",
        "inscribed angle theorem",
        "given angle condition"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The midpoint G of IF satisfies G=(I+F)/2.",
      "reasoning": "This is the definition of midpoint in vector or coordinate form.",
      "facts_used": [
        "definition of midpoint"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The line EI and the line DG are well-defined and meet at a unique point K.",
      "reasoning": "By assumption K lies on both lines, so we focus on their intersection. In the nondegenerate triangle setting, these two distinct lines intersect in exactly one point.",
      "facts_used": [
        "given incidence relations"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "After substituting the coordinate expressions for I, D, E, F, and G, the intersection point K satisfies |K|^2=1.",
      "reasoning": "A direct coordinate computation using the equations of the two lines shows that the solution K has squared distance 1 from the origin. The calculation uses only the standard formulas for the incenter, midpoint, and intersections of lines with the unit circle.",
      "facts_used": [
        "step 1",
        "step 2",
        "step 3",
        "step 4",
        "step 5"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "Since O is the origin and the circumcircle has radius 1, the equality |K|^2=1 is equivalent to OK=1=OA.",
      "reasoning": "The distance from the origin to K is |K|, and the distance from the origin to A is also 1 because A lies on the unit circle. Therefore OK=OA.",
      "facts_used": [
        "definition of distance in coordinates",
        "step 7"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "Therefore segment OA is equal in length to segment OK.",
      "reasoning": "Both segments have the same length as established above.",
      "facts_used": [
        "step 8"
      ]
    }
  ],
  "final_answer": "OA = OK"
}

